<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title><%= pageTitle %> – Art of the Orient</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <%- include('partials/header', { headerClass, pageTitle }) %>
  <main class="main">
    <h2 class="gallery-title"><%= pageTitle %></h2>
    <section class="section-text section-text-full">
      <p>Jingyeong sansuhwa (진경산수화), or "true-view landscape painting," emerged in the Joseon dynasty as painters turned from idealized Chinese-style mountains to the actual scenery of the Korean peninsula. Artists traveled to famous sites — the Diamond Mountains, Mount Geumgang, coastal and river views — and recorded them with a distinctive sense of place, combining documentary interest with ink wash and color to create a uniquely Korean landscape tradition.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <script src="/js/nav.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
